{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_douglasfir_ver01/data/sn86075189/00414211045/1957081601/0403.xml":{"full_text":"Editorial\nMore Fuel To Feed Inflation\n___ i o m y-, i i\nThe Mountain states TgI. Toi. Company lias petitioned\nthe state Public Service Commission for approval of a new\nschedule of business and residential rates ranging from 30 to\n40 per cent above current schedules.\nIn so doing the telephone monopoly reminds Montana peo\npie that the company has not had a rate increase since 19o3\nand that, in the years since, the cost of providing service\nparticularly labor\u2014has gone up substantially. In its adver\ntising, the utility convevs the impression that wages have been\nincreased by about forty per cent. Such a conclusion is patently'\nerroneous as any telephone company worker will tell you\u2014\nthat much of the increased outlay for wage payments is due\nto greatly expanded operations by MST&T in the last four\nyears, necessitating the hiring of more manpower.\nThe company also points to tax increases as another reason\nwhy rates should be increased. It is true that the last legislature\ndid vote a moderate increase in the telephone license tax and\nother taxes paid by corporate enterprise. It is also true that\nthat same legislature voted to reimburse utilities to the extent\nof 75 per cent of the cost of relocating their lines whenever a\nhighway relocation is made. In view of the greatly expanded\nhighway program which is now getting underway it is a fair\nassumption the new reimbursement program will more than\noffset the higher taxes the telephone company is liable fori\nj.\nbecause of legislative action.\nThe company s pointing up that it has had no rate increase\nsince 1953 while most other goods and services have continued\nto rise in price the past four years, warrants more exhaustive\ndetailing than the few lines on this score in its recent state\nwide advertising under heading \"Information Regarding Pro-1\nposed Increase In Telephone Rates.\nIn 1953, it should be recalled, MST&T received an avei*age\nincrease of 25 cent in spite of the efforts of the then At\ntorney General, Arnold Olsen, to have that large increase\nvoided by the courts as being unwarranted, unreasonable and\n\u2022unjust\". That 1953 rate increase was the third or fourth sub-1\nNow, the company is coming forward and asking that rate|\nstantiai rate increase granted the company since 1947.\nincreases ranging from 30 to 40 per cent be approved on the\nplea that it must have more revenue to meet increasing labor\ntax and equipment costs and to attract investors' capital. Such\na plea might have some validity if inflation had reduced the\nbuying power of the dollar a comparable percentage in the|\nsame four-year period. For all the fact that in 15 of the last\nlo months the cost of living has increased, the value of the\ndollar has dropped only about ten per cent over the last four\nyears\u2014most of the drop coming in the last 16 months.\nLikewise, from reading the brief announcements on quarter\nly dividends paid stockholders by MST&T, it does not appear\nthat the utility is suffering the same pinch as are other busi\n\nnesses and individuals because of the weakening dollar. Tele\nphone company dividends, unlike the probable 1957 dividends\nof the Anaconda Company, for example, are holding their own\nin spite of the rising costs the utility's ads refer to.\nBecause an unreasonably high rate increase was granted\nMST&T in August 1953 that utility has been able to expand and\nprosper while other segments of the state's economy have found\nthemselves increasingly harder pressed to make ends meet in\nthe face of rising costs and a deteriorating economy particularly\nin agriculture, mining and lumber.\nThe requested 30 to 40 per cent rate increases will only\nadd more fuel to the inflationary spiral at a time when the\nMontana economy generally is fighting a losing battle to fend\noff impending depression. There is grave doubt whether\na portion of the requested rate increases is justified in even\nthe smallest degree.\neven\nThe Readers' Forum\nNeed At Least One Free\nPress In Each State\nBear Harry Gretchen;\nEnclosed please find $13.00 for which\npiease renew my subscription from the\nabove, sum. Also there are two new\naddresses for subscriptions, and the\nrest is a donation.\nIt is shocking to realize that there\nare still not enough people in Montana\nwho realize the worth of the Peoples\nVoice to support it as it should be sup\nported. I sincerely hope that the \"end\"\nfor the People's Voice is not at hand,\nf rather like to believe that this is just\nanother cycle.\nNow, memories come back to me of\nthe very beginning of the Voice. Those\ncold winter evenings during January\nand February 1937, when we met many\ntimes in the back banquet room of\nBrady's and formulated the policies\nthat were to govern the newspaper\nwhich we hoped to create. The picture\nis clearly in front of me now, 20 years\nn\nTHE PEOPLE'S VOICE\nPublished weekly by The People's\nVoice Publishing Co.,at 1205 Lockey\nStreet, Helena. Montana.\nHARRY L. BILLINGS, Editor\nEntered as Second Class Matter De\ncember 7. 1S39, at the Post Office at\nHelena, Montana, under the Act of\nMarch 3, 1879.\nSubscription Price: $3.00 a Year\nNo Commercial Advertising except\nfrom Co-operative Business institu\ntions accepted. Rates on application.\n.V\nB\u2014\nlater, of those wonderful men and some\nwomen too, who did the spade work,\nand those who incorporated the People's\nVoice. We should remind ourselves, too,\nthat this happened in the dark days\nof 1937, and the Voice didn't publish\nuntn 1939. That was the Session when\nSoclal Security was first set up in\nMontana to conform to the National\nAct. How to merely feed our people\nwas a big question at that time. We\ndidn't a ways \"k n ow ^how t o ^g\u00e9t^ t h era\nNow, 20 years later, we have passed\n'L\u00ef? \"prosperity\",\nand are fa'Cing^ some or the same thing's\nwe faced then. People right now are\nnot willing to believe they can possibly\nbe confronted with anything but more\n\"prosperity\". In this interval, people\nco-ope f ratTo n n d bTtwJln^pfop^ea They\nhave had their tummies full and have\nnot been willing to band together for\na common cause. But our needs are the\nsame as they were in 1937.\ne need a paper that is free to ex\npress the truth as we know the truth\nto be, without fear that someone will\ntake the advertising away from us. We\ndon't have any advertising, and must\nnever have any if we are to speak the\ntruth.\nHere I am only hitting the high\nspots Of the things I have in mind, for\nthere isn't room to tell everything as\nit should be told. I hope the people of\nMontana will not allow the People s\nVoice to collapse. There should be at\nleast one Free Paper in each s<tate,\nfree to tell the truth. It is my greatest\nhope that the Voice will continue to go\nforward, and it will if everyone will i\nput their shoulders to the wheel. Kind\nest regards and best wishes from the\nBurns'.\u2014-ERNIE BURNS, Seattle (form\nerly of Whitefish).\nWHA T DO YOU THINK?\nBy GRETCHEN G. BILLINGS\nWe have been back from our vaca\nLjon a week now. During the first\nweek we traveled into Canada. It\nwas very pretty, and we are glad we\nsaw it, but we have decided the great\nf n b b u re 15 ,s r,sht ,n our\nwhatever pleasure we had the first\nI week of our vacation was overshad\nowed the last week when we lost our\n(larIia g littlest granddaughter. She\ninfection conquered her tiny body,\nShe was here such a short time we\ndidn't even get to know her, but our\nhearts ache none the less because\nJ. he S01 T\u00b0\u2122 f losm s her Her\nand it is als0 har for their Mother\nan d Dad to see them have to face\nsuch heartbreak,\ning for an increase in electrical rates\nLame as no surprise because the ru\nmor had been going around for sev\neral months.\nIf Montana Power needs more\nmoney for new construction it looks\nlike the people of Montana would be\nbetter off to do like the Republican\nstate of Nebraska and create a state\nelectrical authority,\nuilc in amort!ze put the cost and\n?ncrea\u00b0sT gmnted fhe'power\ncompany will include taxes, that they\nsay have increased 146% in the past\nten years. We pay the taxes for pri\nThe announcement Wednesday af\nternoon that Montana Power is ask\ndo our own\nv ate even the private utili\ntax paying private utilities\nnothing.' They are tax collectors,\nnothing more. We might as well own\nthe P ubIic utilities. If we make up\nthe taxes in some other manner we\n\nmeans\nwould still be getting our power\ncheap enough to be well ahead of\nj the game in the long run.\nincrease and the Attorney General\nb Jf s the uth r ^y to act in behalt of\nL state supi em e court decision writ\n(ten several years ago by Justice Al\nThere will be opposition to the\nbert Angstman\u201e\nTaxes are going to be the subject\nof a lot of kicking around in the\ncoming months. Republicans are go\ning to be centering their arguments\naround the fact the last legislature\nincreased income taxes 40%, and\nthat 13 su PP\u00b0 sed t0 make y\u00b0 u mad\nfor middle income people doesn't j\namount to much more than what the\nIt doesn't make me especially mad.\nIf all other taxes were eliminated and\nwe just paid income taxes on a com\nparative basis we might have reason\ntor screamin',\nAnd we might get more equality\nin the taxation business, too.\nA 40% increase in income taxes\nNo. 1 Kennel Dog Ferrets Out the Villain\nSays Farmers Cause of Inflation\nEDITOR'S NOTE: Defense Secretary Charley Wilson, who, in his tenure in the Eisenhower Administra\ntion has been chronically afflicted with \"hoof-in-mouth\" disease, gave forth with another dilly a few days\nback. The following short radio broadcast from Farmers Union Grain Terminal Association one day last\nweek needs no elaboration from this source.\nj n Washington, they are beating the bushes, turn\n\ning over stones and old logs, looking for the cause of\n\nthis inflation that is squeezing all our pocketbooks.\nNoW alon S COmeS a felloW wh he knoWS whei e\nto find the cause, and he gives out the profound ob\nserva tion that farmers and city dwellers are the num\nber one and two villians.\nT t /-.c i tt titm\nBe is Charles E. Wilson, who has been Secretary\nof Defense, and at that job, has spent billions for the\nmilitai X He s the spendingest man in Washington,\nHe blames inflation on the Administration's tight\nm0 ney policy on big wage increases, and on farm\niallu\nsubsidies. Wilson came to Eisenhower's cabinet from\nGeneral Motors, where he was head man. When it\n\ncomes to spending money, Mr. Wilson has set a stag\ngering pace. Maybe it is necessary all this defense\n\nspending. VV e ve got to spend if we are to have de\nfenses.\n\nBe that as it may, Secretary of Defense Wilson,\nwhatever his views on defense, or General Motors\nT TT r.\nand what is good for the U. S., makes it clear that\nhe thinks laboring people and farmers are reallv\n\ncausing inflation, along with the government's high\ninterest rates. Wilson says, \"The effort to get farm\ngoing on all the time is making the dollar less valu\nprices up, the extra subsidies for farmers that\nare\nable.'' He conceded that there might be some\nreason\nimposition of a sales tax would have\nmeant, and income tax is based on\nability. No, I will pay my percentage\nof income tax, because then when i\nhave income I pay, and most of any\nthing I want to keep an income.\nBut in all this tax talk let's get a\nfew questions ready for the boys\nLet's ask them if they would vote for\nbill to close the loopholes in the\ncorporation license tax\u2014and let's get\na little conversation on the subject\nso the corporations can't continue to\nmaneuver the legislative committee\ninto killing such a bill before it gets\non the floor of the House.\na\nk them if they would vote\nfor collecting taxes from the fellow\nliving in some other state who owns\nthe rental unit down the street or\nthe adjoining acres, or gets income\nfrom the natural resources that should\nbe helping our economy along, but\npays no income tax here.\nLet's ask them if they would vote\nfor a sales tax instead of increased\nincome taxes.\nThe psychology for the next session\nof the legislature is going to be to\ntry and bring about a fatalistic atti\ntude toward a sales tax. In 1957 they\nmanaged to increase income taxes\n40% and not correct other existing\ninequalities, and next time they will\nhave the background laid for a sales\ntax and you can bet your bottom dol\nlar (and it may be) the sales tax\nwill be maneuvered into position as\nLet's as\nthe only source,\nI don't think the people of Montana\nshould listen to any talk on a sales\ntax, period.\nI think we should insist on seeing\nthe color of the money that will come\nfrom the Montana income of the out\nof-stater and the corporation license\ntax of the out-of-state corporation,\nbefore we even dignify conversation\non a sales tax.\nThese fellows who talk sales tax\nmust recognize the economic situation\nisn't so good and if some of us aren't\ngoing to have so much in the way of\nincomes they want to be sure we\n\"feel like we are contributing to gov\nernment\".\nThen these fellows who are doing\na lot of hollering and trying to pin\nthe blame, were mostly the ones who\ndid little constructive expression on\nthe tax situation in Helena in Janu\nary. They couldn't get their eyes off\nthe ragged pocket in the jeans of the\nfellow who doesn't have any income\nto pay taxes on, and who has a devil\nof a time paying for anything\u2014but of\ncourse it worries the man with a lot\nof money about the fact the guy with\nnothing doesn't \"feel like he is con\ntributing to government\".\nI was far from happy with the way\nthe majority party approached the\ntax situation, and the results they\nbrought about left much to be de- 1\nsired, but let's keep things in per-1\nfoi tossing the farmers a lifeline, becase^ as he put\nit, \"if you are going to let the workman'and\nfacturer get away with higher wages and prices, you\nhave to have\nfarmers.\"\nmanu\nsome protection for the unorganized\nJust to see what is happening with inflation, let's\nook at some figures. When you compare 1947 with\nabout a t er >-year period, you find that corpora\ntion profits after taxes have gone up 19%, Dividend\npayments to stockholders have gone up 69% The\namount of\nmoney that lenders receive because of\nR 1.1 mtei est rates, which Mr. W'ilson says is a factor\n0 am for lnf lation, has gone up 93%.\nAnd, how have farmers fared? Well, their net in-\ncome m the last ten years has gone down 25%. That's\nngnt farm net income is down 25% from 1947\nlevels But still Mr. Wilson insists that farm subsidies\ncon i, m e to inflation. And, that is not without its\nouc o uonic humor\u2014the spendingest man in the\nnation blaming farmers for inflation. Of course, Mr.\n1 S n 1S no u; onl y cabinet member who is con\nsed about the economic situation. Farmers are well\nAgl\u00efc^e, W who E ha' BGnS n f\nincome-wise.\nY U hear<J n the news tha t Mr. Wilson\nthe cabinet, W'e\npushed them back 20 years,\nis now leav\ncan only suggest that Mr. Benson\naccompany him.\nspective We would have found our\nselves even worse off if the minority\nparty had had its way.\nIt'would simply have been a sales\nand that would have amounted to\nincrease and been a\ntax\nabout the same\nlot more unfair.\nother solution did the Re\nWhat\npublicans offer?\nThe Governor told us in his state\nof the state address in January that\nfaced with wolves or cre\nhanded the legislature a 90\nwe were\nmation\nmillion dollar budget with no recom\nmendations, and only raised his voice\nwhen the people were relieved of I\ntax and then to protest\ncent on gas\nthe reduction in taxes.\nIs Ike Planning-\n(Continued From Page One;\n\"So the outlook now is for a 're\nadjustment' some time in 1958.\nSylvia Porter, economic writer for\nthe Hall Syndicate, pot the Adminis\ntration policy into even blunter lan\nguage. She reported that policy-mak\nand influential economists in\nWashington have been telling her\noff-the-record:\n\"What we need to end ike wage\nthis country it a\n\nors\nprice spiral in\nlittle recession, and the quicker it\nthe better.\n\"Nothing big or severe, of course\n\u2014oh no. But enough unemployment\nthroughout the country to push the\nback into line. Enough worry\ncomes\nunions\nabout the state of the economy and\nto force business\npublic resistance\nmen to back down on price increases\nand to find other ways to cover costs.\"\nKerr asked 1 reasury Under Secre\ntary W.\nJournal and the Lawrence articles,\nI Burgess called \"both very ingenious\nand interesting\", but refused to ad\nmit that eithe\nrepresents Adminis\ntration policy.\"\nThe Journal of Commerce, which\nheartily applauds the recession idea,\nrefuses to believe the denials.\nAfter all, said the Journal in a re\ncent editorial, \"it is unthinkable that\nanyone in high public office could\ncome out 'in favor' of any recession,\neven a tiny one\n\"When it comes to interpretation\nof such elusive subjects as economic\npolicy goals, the soundest advice pos\nsible is to base such judgments on\nwhat the responsible authorities are\ndoing instead of paying too much\nattention to what they are saying.\"\nSenator Kerr told THE MACHIN\ntheir voices heard in letters to the\nPresident and Congress\n1ST last week:\n\"During these Finance Committee\nhearings, we've done our best to show\nwhat the Administration planners are\nactually doing.\n\"If they continue the present high\ninterest, hard money, tight credit poli\ncies, a recession and mass unemploy\nment will be inevitable.\n\"Only an aroused public opinion\ncan put a stop to this madness. 1 hope\nthat members of the IAM will make","height":"20097","width":"13707"}}
